All smells related to the production of warmth are nostalgic and pleasant: burning wood in a fireplace, furnaces, central heating, radiators turned on for the first time in autumn, old car heating systems, even the plastic fumes evaporating off a cheap space heater bring comfort.

Dr. Peat has mentioned how generally the smokey flavors of burned meats, cigarettes and tobacco (ideally no drug should be consumed by burning and inhalation), grilled vegetables to char, soot, etc. are all generally estrogenic and "bad", but people still tend to like them a lot.
Gypsy?

Anything that reminds us of combustion, heat, fires, the metabolites of the primal process delights us. Junger would say the primal fire around which early mankind huddled exists today in heated car seats, smoked bacons, oil heaters, in pipes, etc. Actually he would not say this.
